			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Read nad tell me what u guys think.... and whether its worth continuing
<br />

<br />
This is medieval fantasy-ish one:
<br />

<br />
The Mayday Joust…
<br />
…the perfect time of year to display one’s talents (or lack thereof) before the capital of the empire; it was a time of celebration, of victories on and off the battlefield. But it was also a time of deceit and or great treachery – as many of the competitors were soon to discover; Claudius Aemillianus, for instance, would soon come to realise that not all lances were blunt at the tips… 
<br />
The charming violet eyed captain of the Empirical Guard – though new to this world of jousting and duelling – was already becoming a favourite among lords and ladies alike and was greeted by the roar of the crowd as he readied himself for battle. 
<br />
The flag was waved and the combatants began to charge at one another at full speed, pushing both themselves and their horses to the limits, each for one’s own cause: perhaps for the price, the recognition, to win the heart of that special spectator amidst the crowd or simply for the sheer joy of battle. But whatever the cause, ends perhaps could never truly justify the means. 
<br />
Claudius was focusing hard at the point of contact he had chosen but through the small slits in the visor it was difficult to keep his eyes while on it riding at such a speed.
<br />
 His opponent was approaching... 
<br />
Several feet… 
<br />
Several inches…
<br />
 
<br />
There was a dull thud as the men landed a blow to one another, but neither fell. The captain felt a sharp pain in his right shoulder for an instant at he was hit but carried on at his murderous pace as the two men charged towards the end of the fence that separated them. Less than a second later, there was a sickening snap of wood as his opponents lance snapped near the tip; splinters of wood and chips of paint flying everywhere.   
<br />
The wounded captain was full of curses as his horse reached the end of the fence, whereon he tore of his helmet and threw it aside in rage. Claudius bit his lip hard then reached for the large bloody wooden splint and removed it from his throbbing right shoulder. “He tipped it…” the weapons master muttered as he took the lance from Claudius.
<br />
“The nerve of the little…” he growled under his breath, “Find me a lighter lance.” 
<br />
The old man shook his head, “Sir…you should dismount now and report the incident; you can’t carry on like this –”  
<br />
“No!” Claudius snapped, “I can’t allow scum like him to win this tournament…” he paused, “who would listen?! The lords can bribe their way out of humiliation but as for me, I have no such luck. I must carry on…”
<br />
The weapons master sighed, “As you wish sir…” he muttered as he handed the captain another lance. Claudius clenched the six foot long piece of wood in his hand, then dropped, “I can’t…” he muttered, flexing his gloved fingers.
<br />
“This is the lightest one I have, Sir.”
<br />
Claudius sighed and thought for a moment, he hadn’t much time before the next run, if he was to forfeit, he may as well do it now. “Tie it to my arm…”
<br />
“Sir –”
<br />
He sighed, “Just do it…there isn’t much time”
<br />

<br />
Claudius could imagine his opponent laughing at him and though he couldn’t see the look on his face through their visors – it must have been one of malice. He inhaled deeply and braced himself for the second run. The flag was raised and dropped, and just as before the men lowered their weapons and charged. These few moments between, for Claudius, were reduced to the sound of pounding hoof beats and the blood in his ears; his mind was consumed with the thought of spilling the little bastard’s blood.
<br />
Three…
<br />
Two…
<br />
One… And die!!! He thought quietly to himself as the side of his lance hit his opponent in the chest, knocking the man backwards off his horse, almost. Claudius watched with great satisfaction as his opponent was dragged toward the other end of the arena; dangling from his horse by the shin greave that had caught in the stirrup. 
<br />
The crowd roared with approval and many silk kerchiefs and flowers were thrown his way as he dismounted his horse. And for a moment, he allowed himself to bask in the warmth of the adoration of the spectators, many of whom were commoners just as he, before marching off to the armoury to change into more comfortable clothing. 
<br />
Claudius breathed a sigh of relief as he sat down on the hard wooden bench next to supply; relieved that he had won, relatively unscathed but more so because he had defeated the cheating nobleman by willpower and not deceit. He knew well that the tipped lance was no accident; it was meant for him. Being one of the few ranking commoners in the Empirical Guard, whom, at the Emperor’s grace were allowed entry into this year Mayday Joust, he was well aware of the fact that he would be subject to ruthless and unfair treatment. 
<br />
 “Ah! There you are!”
<br />
He turned around to see his commanding officer, the retired General Augustus, standing at the threshold with a handsome young man Claudius had never seen before. Claudius immediately got to his feet, clicked his heels and saluted. Augustus and the other man returned the gesture then approached.
<br />
“Claudius, this is your new commander whom I’ve spoken so much of late, the honourable General Marcius Nero Camillus, son of the Duke of Versailles.”
<br />
The captain saluted again, “It is an honour sir” he muttered with false enthusiasm. August had spoken for months about dispatching Claudius and his men elsewhere to train recruits with another general. He’d always thought of it as nothing but nonsense and now the day has come, Claudius was sure – as he had forever been – that he didn’t want to leave his comfortable position in the Empirical Guard to live in barracks with the regulars. 
<br />
“General Camillus will –”
<br />
“Captain, you’re bleeding!”
<br />
Claudius glanced at his shoulder and the blood running down the shiny metal of his breastplate, “It’s…nothing…” he stammered.
<br />
“I’m sure that it is nothing serious, Captain Aemillianus is a medic and is quite capable of caring for himself” Augustus muttered as he began to walk off, his new commander gave Claudius another anxious look before following the old man outside. The captain breathed a sigh of relief as he unfastened and set aside his armour – his shoulder was throbbing, but he couldn’t treat himself here: there were far too many people walking about and furthermore he was lacking the necessary tools.  
<br />
He stalked out of one of the arena, and though much of the city was taking part in the tournament, there were still many who were busy buying and trading in the crowded streets. Claudius glanced here and there; making several stops along the way before returning to his quarters at the top of the Eastern guard tower. 
<br />

<br />
Sitting amongst the lords and ladies of one of the high tables, Claudius felt strangely out of place. He felt belittled wedged between Augustus and Camillus and all the more so as he glanced across the table at those around him. 
<br />
Though he felt quite presentable in uniform, knee length riding boots with a black velvet cape draped over his left shoulder, his attire looked like peasants’ rags compared to the richly adorned nobility in silk and damask. And while they worn countless precious stones and pearls around their necks; dangled them from their ears and displayed them on the circlets and caps set upon their brows and on their clothes, Claudius wore only a ring around the fourth finger of his left hand.
<br />

<br />
“How is your shoulder, Captain?” Camillus asked quietly.
<br />
“Fine, thank you, sir.”
<br />
Camillus nodded, “Why did you not report that your opponent’s lance had been tipped?” he asked with a frown.
<br />
Claudius shrugged, “I did not think that anyone would listen” he replied, “Anyhow, things of this sort are not uncommon at the tournament.”
<br />
The general laughed, “A decade ago it was, but today this is a serious offence…”
<br />
“Don’t trouble yourself general” Claudius muttered, “It was nothing…”
<br />
He didn’t like this new general, under Augustus he could do as he pleased but under this new commander, who was already watching him like a hawk, Claudius had an uncanny feeling that things were going to be quite different. 
<br />
The idea of leaving suddenly became all the less appealing. 
<br />
Captain Aemillianus spent the rest of the night staring at the food before him and taking the occasional sip of wine while he listened to the conversation and gossip around him, all of which were of no interest to him. Though Camillus and Augustus made an effort to include Claudius in their conversations – they failed horribly – and by the end of the evening, the young captain was almost already fast asleep.
<br />

<br />
Claudius was hardly surprised at the reaction he received from his men in the mess hall the following morning when he told them the news. The general had given him the details of the warning order as they left the banquet hall. Claudius and his men were to make the fortnight long trek from the capital to the northern province of Cytheira.  
<br />
“Captain…this isn’t very amusing,” one of the lieutenants muttered, “Please tell us that you were only poking fun…”
<br />
He shook his head, “That was the order” he said patiently, “we are leaving in five days for the Sethlans…”
<br />
“You mean the mountains in that frozen wasteland of a province?” one of the men snapped, “I refuse to go…”
<br />
Claudius laughed, “First of all. It’s only cold in the winter and second of all I’m not giving you a choice, Longinus…”
<br />
The men burst into laughter but some of them remained solemn, clearly disturbed by the warning order. Claudius knew well that none of his 300 men stationed here would ever want to leave their comfortable posts on the walls of Marseilles. They were well fed, well clothed and better paid than any battalion in the empire – why would anyone in their right minds have any wish to leave? 
<br />
But what troubled Claudius was the fact that Augustus had chosen to send him and his men to the Sethlans rather than that of Captain Silveira whose battalion was also stationed here as soldiers of the Empirical Guard. If Augustus truly favoured Claudius, he would have tried his hardest to keep him in Marseilles. Nevertheless, Claudius still liked to believe that it was neither his mentor’s choice nor intention to send him away and that it was the decision of Emperor Aurelius.    
<br />

<br />
Claudius returned to his quarters after the morning meal and gloomily began composing a note to his family. He had only five days and an entire battalion to ready for a long journey; there simply wasn’t enough to return home. And even if he could, he’d rather not, especially when Cassius was so cross with him.
<br />

<br />
Dear All,
<br />
Sorry for the short notice but I am leaving for the Sethlans. I haven’t the foggiest idea as to when and whether I will return. But I will write as often as I can and return home the first opportunity I have; I simply don’t have the time now.  Please take care of yourselves.
<br />
Claudius
<br />

<br />
The journey from the seaboard capital of the south to the frozen wastelands of the north lasted a little than two weeks but had felt like an eternity. First there was the storm which brought in inconceivable quantities of rain to the entire southern region for three days; everything was wet from the tents to the food. And long trek through the marshes that followed did little to improve their spirits.
<br />
Then there was the forest: days of being pestered by insects and having their food stolen by rodents. One company even had the luck of encountering a bear on their ventures to find nourishment. However, things did begin to look upward as the forest began to change and thin out.
<br />
 Broadleaved trees gave way to mixtures of deciduous and needle leafed trees but after a few days the leafed trees disappeared all together and evergreen trees were all that remained. While the environment around them improved and the tall ancient trees thinned out into dwarf-like bushes and shrubs, they encountered other problems – the lack of food and clean water. There were no streams or ponds in this drier part of the continent and though the lively vegetation consisting of a dozen different kinds of grass and a handful of bushes of sorts, there was nothing to eat.
<br />
When they finally did arrive; Claudius had never seen his men so relieved to behold snow-capped mountains or barren plains studded with moss covered rocks. It seemed foolish to think that anyone would rejoice in their arrival at such a place, but after two weeks of treacherous conditions in the wilderness, it was evident that all would gladly welcome a bed and warm food (even if it was in the middle of nowhere).
<br />
Captain Aemillianus was shown his way around the barracks by his new commander as his men were ushered into the mess hall for a lovely evening meal of dried salted pork and barely gruel. The entire place carried an air of antiquity; from the courtyard to the stone gargoyles jutting out of the walls of the soldiers’ barracks, everything was built in the likeness of century-old architecture.    
<br />
“Your men will sleep in here, forty to a room” Camillus muttered as he pushed open one of the doors in the west wing. The room stunk of mildew and rotting wood with double bunked beds lined from the front of the room to the wall at the back. Between each bunk was a small chest, or drawer for personal belonging. Claudius bit his lip, what would his men say to this?
<br />
Camillus shut the door quietly and walked on ahead and turned to face across the courtyard, “my quarters can be found there” he told Claudius then turned and walked on. Stopping at the last door in the wing he spoke again, “These are the officer’s barracks…” The captain nodded and inhaled deeply; he had been far too spoiled by Augustus – the idea of sharing quarters was unknown to him. “With my six captains, the room is full” Camillus continued, “I’ll direct you to your private quarters; it’s a little further but I’m sure you wouldn’t mind.”   
<br />

<br />
Claudius sat alone at a table, far from the other officers in the mess hall. The men had long since gone to unpack their things. Different food had been laid out for them: dried venison, cheese, bread, dried fruits and mead – all luxuries compared to the tasteless grey slush him men had been served. The food sat before Claudius, untouched, it was surprising how one’s stomach could shrink in a matter of two weeks. He busied himself instead by reading a battle tactics manual while taking occasional sips of the wine while he listened to the conversation around him.
<br />
It quickly became clear that they were unwanted here. Just my luck…Claudius thought; he’d put his men through two weeks of torture to bring them to a barren wasteland, only to be despised by the others…
<br />
“Is this seat taken?” suddenly snapping him out of his train of thought.
<br />
He looked up from his book to see a young soldier standing before him, also a captain, judging by his attire. “No.” Claudius replied then turned back to his book and eavesdropping. 
<br />
“I’m Antonius” the young man introduced himself and stuck out his hand for Claudius to shake, “pleased to meet you Captain Aemillianus”
<br />
“The honour is mine, Captain Antonius…” he muttered as they shook hands.
<br />
“How do you like it here?”
<br />
Claudius shrugged, “I’ve been here but a few hours” he said with a soft chuckle, “But I suppose it’s alright the climate here is quite different from what we are used to…”
<br />
Antonius nodded, “Your men don’t seem too pleased to be here…”
<br />
“The journey was very difficult for them – it’ll be a few days before they are… shall we say…themselves again” Claudius muttered with a forced smile. 
<br />
The other captain nodded, “Our men aren’t making matters any better are they?”
<br />
“I don’t understand, Captain Antonius” Claudius muttered.
<br />
“By the way, Captain Aemillianus, you can simply refer to me as Marcus, I see no need for such formalities” he said with a genuine smile, then went on to explain his comment, “No doubt you have heard the comments of the other captains or was perhaps even confronted with their hostility.”
<br />
Claudius shook his head, “These are your barracks and we are the invaders here, after all…” he said with a forced smile as he stood to his feet, “Enjoy your meal, Captain, I must be off now…” he muttered, clicked his heels, saluted then left.
<br />

<br />
Captain Aemillianus could hear the muttering of complaints long before he reached the theatre, where he had told his men to gather. But none of it was what he didn’t already know: the food was tasteless and bland; the states of their living quarters were atrocious and unfit for even the lowliest of livestock; their new comrades were rude and inhospitable. Claudius inhaled deeply and braced himself for a crowd of angry men as he pushed opened the door but there was nothing, only silence. The men all stood to their feet, clicked their heels in unison and saluted, “Good evening sir!”
<br />
 “This clearly, is not a good evening!” he shouted, “Men, how many times have you been told – lying before an officer is a serious offence!” Claudius snapped as he stood before them and his men burst into laughter. 
<br />
 “Let me remind you, men… Why are we here?!” he went on.
<br />
Several of them shook their heads and muttered amongst themselves.
<br />
“We came because we’re the best of the best!” he yelled, “Thus, behave like so!”
<br />
His remark was met with more mutterings of disapproval. 
<br />
Claudius sighed, “Who are we here to serve?”
<br />
“The Empire!” several men shouted in reply.
<br />
“Then why are we allowing ourselves to be trampled upon by them?!” he shouted, “Who are they to put us down? Had they been competent, the Emperor would not have sent for us! But let not your pride be your downfall. From this day forth, men, I will not tolerate another complaint.” he told them, “We are not the best merely because of the names and titles we have been given and we must show ourselves to be true soldiers of the empire – civilized and valiant!”
<br />
The men cheered and applauded this speech as Claudius clicked his heels, saluted and left the crowded theatre, feeling no more at ease then when he had entered. He was good at this; spurting lies of sorts to raise their spirits, lies which even he did not believe. He had his own theories as to why they had been sent here. 
<br />
 “Do you honestly believe what you told your men?”
<br />
Claudius was startled by the voice and turned around to see General Camillus stand several feet from him; the captain immediately clicked his heels and saluted then muttered ‘good evening’.
<br />
“Well?” Camillus sneered as he fell into step beside the young captain.
<br />
He shook his head, “Men are simple creatures; if you patronize them they will listen and if you bribe them, they will obey” he replied, “my battalion is no better than any other in this empire…”
<br />
“Then why do you think they were sent here?” Camillus asked.
<br />
 The captain laughed bitterly, “because I am young and we are dispensable, sir”
<br />
“Hmm?” the general raised an eyebrow, “I don’t quite follow…”
<br />
Claudius sighed, “Word of an uprising has reached the emperor, no doubt” he began, “Let us not keep secret amongst ourselves, general, it is evident that we were sent here to defend the north-western border; to suppress the rebellion…”
<br />
Camillus nodded, “Then I will be honest with you captain – I am here for this very reason; young and dispensable, just as you are…” he said with a sigh, “but we won’t allow ourselves to be easily disposed of will we, captain?”
<br />
“No, sir…”
<br />
“You don’t believe that either, do you?”
<br />
Claudius did not, or rather could not reply.
<br />
“Anyhow, it is late.” Camillus muttered after a short pause, “Good night.”
<br />
“Yes sir.” He muttered with a salute before walking off.
<br />

<br />
“You’re a soldier, not a lady of the court!” Claudius shouted at the soldier he was duelling, “Fight like one!”
<br />
The soldier glared at him but said nothing.
<br />
“Charge at me, weakling!” the captain yelled to provoke the boy who in turn did as he was told but was repelled and thrown aside, “You don’t charge aggressively enough!” Claudius muttered as he turned around, sheathed his sword and walked away. He could hear the boy cursing as he got to his feet and picked up his sword but did not see what was to come. The boy charged again, “Is this aggressive enough for you captain!?” he shouted as he charged for Captain Aemillianus and cut him across the back from the tip of his right arm to the shoulder blade of his left. Claudius turned around with a murderous look in his eyes, “What do you think you’re doing, soldier?”
<br />
“Charging aggressively…” the boy snapped.
<br />
Claudius nodded, “Charging?” he demanded, “Charging?! You –”
<br />
The general stepped forth, snatched the sword from the captain and poised it at the soldier but Claudius reached out and grabbed Camillus’ wrist with a look of disapproval before letting go. “You’re too kind, captain” the general growled then struck the soldier hard across the face with the flat of the blade, “I would have killed him…” 
<br />
“Permission to leave sir…” Claudius muttered.
<br />
Camillus sighed and rolled his eyes, “Dear God, Claudius! Of course!” he exclaimed as followed the captain toward his quarters, “Send the boy home. He is not to set foot in this camp or any others in the empire!” he ordered as he left. 
<br />
“I can take care of myself, general” Claudius muttered.
<br />
The general laughed, “I don’t doubt your skill, Captain but when you are bleeding pools from your back – I don’t see how you are able to help yourself.”
<br />
“Sir, I’d rather do this myself.” Claudius pleaded as he painfully pushed open the door to let himself inside but Camillus shook his head and entered after him, “Why?” he whispered into his ear, “Because, you’re really a woman?”
<br />
The colour drained from the captain’s face for an instant, “Sir. I –”
<br />
“That, we will discuss later; but for now, your wound needs attention.”
<br />
Claudius sat down in her chair and slowly began to remove her torn and blood sodden jacket and undershirt with her back facing Camillus. The sword had conveniently cut through the cloth bidding her chest and there was no need to fumble with it. The captain, with her head bowed and fists clenched; brooded about what would become of her while the general carefully cleaned and dressed her wound.
<br />
“What do you propose I do with you woman?” Camillus sneered, “Send you away in shame? Or have you executed?”
<br />
She wrung her fingers in her hands but said nothing, there was nothing to say. After years of keeping her identity well hidden, she had been discovered and not by a mere soldier but by her commander.
<br />
The general chuckled, “I was only poking fun, Claudius. No harm shall befall you…” he told her reassuringly, “I’ve actually known for quite sometime and was simply seeking an opportunity to ask you…” he explained, “Why do you think I assigned you private quarters when there were empty bunks in the officer’s barracks?”
<br />
Claudius breathed a small sigh of relief but was cut short by Camillus’ questions.
<br />
“Why in the world did you enlist?” he asked, “Women your age ought to be home rearing children….”
<br />
She scoffed, “Is that what you think of us, sir?”
<br />
“No….well…I’ll be honest, yes” he said, “Until this day I have never seen a woman do anything but…” Camillus sighed, “What drove you to give up the joys of womanhood for this hellhole?”
<br />
“I have my reasons…”
<br />
He laughed, “I know your reasons. Augustus has told me that you work hard to feed your little peasant family: the widowed mother, sister, brother-in-law and your little niece” he stopped for a moment, “but you’re not really one of them are you?”
<br />
“I don’t understand…”
<br />
“You’re well educated, for one and …” he let his voice trail off. Claudius didn’t dare question him and let the comment go; dismissing it as product of the general’s curiosity. There was no way he could have remembered or let alone discovered her past.
<br />

<br />
Marcius was filled ecstasy as he stepped out of Claudius’ quarters and shut the door behind him. It was her…His childhood friend, his long lost bride to be. But he couldn’t tell her so; he couldn’t tell anyone.
<br />
 From the beginning there had been something vaguely familiar about his handsome new captain, almost too beautiful to be called handsome. When he had caught a glimpse of her bathing, suspicions had suddenly turned into a possible reality. Now he had seen the black dragon – crest of the Adelfius family tattooed on her left shoulder blade, his doubts were confirmed. And he wondered whether the porcelain doll of his childhood still remembered him.<br />_________________<br /><img src="http://i48.photobucket.com/albums/f205/ds_mikage/Shinimegamicopy.jpg" border="0" /></span><span class="gensmall"><br /><br />Last edited by k4kashi on Wed Feb 22, 2006 8:35 am; edited 1 time in total</span></td>
