			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">This one is a futuristic one about assasins...
<br />

<br />

<br />
Life carried on despite the dreary overcast sky shrouding the city in its bone chilling drizzle. Three men, each with their own bodyguards exited their respective vehicles, seemingly engaged in an intriguing conversation that lasted as they stepped into the elevator and back out again on the 31st floor. Silence befell them as they walked grimly down the long corridor to the meeting room. Each man was now consumed in his own thoughts; for each one of them, today was just like any other winter day. It had never occurred to any of them that something extraordinary would take place today, or that there was a sniper perched upon the roof of the adjacent building, waiting for them.
<br />
As swiftly as she had come, the sniper disappeared. Having fired three silent but fatal shots, she fled from the hiding spot and re-entered the building; merging effortlessly into the crowd of office crawling returning home after a days work in the concrete jungle. She glared at the emergency vehicles parked in front of the building as she climbed into the car and set down the briefcase in the passenger seat. Her presence had been but three penny sized holes in a skyscraper window –they would never find her…
<br />

<br />
‘Cuz every time we touch I feel the rhythm
<br />
            And every time we kiss I reach for the sky
<br />

<br />
“The weather outside is shit…” one of the customers muttered to the bartender who was busy mixing the strawberry daiquiri he had ordered.
<br />
The young bartender nodded and smiled, “Sadly, we’re not any busier than usual”, he said as he place the cocktail before the man. He glanced anxiously at the clock 6:15 – it wasn’t like her to be late…He sat down with a sigh and watched while the small crowd danced and swayed to the music.
<br />

<br />
                        I want you to know, I need you by my side…
<br />

<br />
He glanced around the nightclub once again. There she was, sitting on a bar stool several meters from him. She sat with her long legs crossed in a way that made them look a mile long, chin resting in the palm of her right hand while the fingers of the other drummed rhythmically on the counter. In her black gothic outfit, with the tail of her leather trench coat falling over the back of the bar stool – she looked like vampire or some obscure goddess of death. 
<br />
He stared at her but she did not return his gaze; she merely stood up then disappeared into the crowd. The bartender smiled to himself – everything was alright. He left then, having spotted the girl who would take over the next shift. He gathered his things and pulling his coat over his shoulders, headed out into the freezing rain.
<br />
There she was again, walking towards the where he stood before the back entrance of The Phoenix. They walked towards one another as if completely unaware of each other’s presence then seemingly ran accidentally into one another as they walked by. The bartender reached a hand into his coat pocket; there was a piece of paper that hadn’t been there before. He would read it once he was truly alone in his car.
<br />
Kai,
<br />
All is well. 
<br />
I am taking your next few missions for you while you recuperate. I’m sure Esmé won’t want you to push yourself too hard in your current state.
<br />
Rae
<br />

<br />
He nodded and smiled as he started the engine – he hated doing what he did and the longer he could put it off, the better. The fact that he had to kill and steal for a living tore him apart every time he set out on a mission. But all he knew was that if he was to go on living he would have to kill. He also wondered also about the others – like Renata and Taylor – who seemed to enjoy what they did. It paid well and they had whatever time left between missions to themselves: partying, clubbing, getting drunk or high and having sex; the nature of their relationship went far beyond a partnership, unlike that of himself and Rae. Contrary to the chirpy and humorous Renata, Rae was quiet, melancholy and never smiled. Keeping to herself most of the time with her running, music and video games when she was not at school, he rarely saw her. 
<br />
At least not until a month ago when he was badly injured in an explosion, whereon she went to see him everyday for two weeks to take care of feed, lean and clothe him, change his dressings and give him morphine to suppress the pain that surged through every limb in his body. He had broken his right forearm in three places, fractured two ribs, broken his tibia and had a strip of steel driven into his left shoulder blade from the sheer force of the blast. He was much better now but the reflection of his scarred body in the mirror still brought back painful memories of the incident –both mentally and physically. 
<br />

<br />
*
<br />
Rae sat down in her usually seat in the music room, glad that the school day was over. She routinely took out her cello from its case, adjusted to the tail pin same height she always did and placed it into the second hole on the donut fixed under front left leg of her chair before removing her bow from its place. 
<br />
Taking a deep breath she began to play, beginning with scales and arpeggios before moving on to pieces. Half a bar into her solo part in the second movement of Rakastava, she stopped, unable to concentrate. Her attention was divided between the music and the boy who stood at the door with a sketchbook in his hand, clearly drawing a picture of her. She set her cello down abruptly and approached him. 
<br />
“May I see that?”
<br />
He nodded and handed it to her, she flipped through it quickly; it was filled with pictures of people, some he had seen before, playing sports, in a pose or just sitting there, the last few were quick but beautiful sketches of her – running on the track, stretching and the latest was an incomplete one of her playing the cello – she had become his new model. Grabbing the pages with drawings of her in her fist, she tore them out of the sketchbook and slowly ripped them to shreds before the boy then handed the book back him. Without another word, Rae returned to her seat and resumed playing as if nothing had happened.
<br />
Several violinists glanced curiously at the art student with a book clutched in is arms and torn paper at his feet as they pushed passed through the door. 
<br />
“What’s his problem?” one of them whispered.
<br />
“Who knows?” said another.
<br />
Practice started in another five minutes and long before then, the art student had disappeared; it bothered her to have someone sneaking around, drawing pictures of her; especially when he had not even bothered to ask for consent. 
<br />
Orchestra passed by rather quickly the two hour long practice felt like a half an hour. And she was more than relieved when she was finally able to go home where there weren’t freaks that hid around the corner to draw –
<br />
Suddenly, her cell phone rang abruptly snapping her out of her train of thought
<br />
“Hello?”
<br />
“It’s Esmé”
<br />
“How was the mission last night?”
<br />
“Fine,” she replied.
<br />
“I will have another one for you soon” Esmé told her, “How long are you planning to do Kai’s tasks for him?”
<br />
Rae paused, “As long as it takes him to recover.”
<br />
“Recover?” Esmé sneered, “I’ve seen what sort of shape he’s in. He is of no further use to me or anyone, as a matter of fact. I want you to terminate him.”
<br />
“M’am –”
<br />
“I’m giving you two weeks to accomplish this task, I’m sure it will be more than enough time…” Esmé sneered then hung up.
<br />
She sighed and snapped her cellphone shut with a loud click; completely awestruck. Kai was Esmé’s pet; she loved, adored him. Why? How? Could she give the order to have him killed? Rae unlocked her car and sat down gloomily inside – putting her head down on the steering wheel – she didn’t have much of a choice…  
<br />
*
<br />
 Two weeks had come and gone in the blink of eye; but while those fourteen days lasted – it felt long, tedious. Today was the deadline and Rae had yet to lift a finger to even prepare to kill him. She stared at the digital clock on her night table as she sat numbly in her chair, it read 21:04. What was she to do?
<br />
The ringing of her cellphone startled her and she reached up to pick up.
<br />
“Hello?”
<br />
“Rae – you haven’t delivered me the body yet…”
<br />
“I’m sorry M’am; I was getting ready to leave –”
<br />
Esmé laughed, “Don’t give me excuses, Rae, just get it done…”
<br />
“Yes, M’am”
<br />
Rae snapped her cellphone shut and threw it against the wall in frustration. 
<br />
“What the fuck is wrong with you?” Renata muttered.
<br />
“Nothing” Rae snapped angrily as she stood up and slowly reached for her coat with a loud sigh then grabbed her gun and keys from the kitchen counter; it was time to pay her partner a little visit.
<br />

<br />
She sat in the apartment in darkness, waiting until he would return. Rae glanced at her watch, 10:15; he would be home soon. His shift at The Phoenix ended at ten on Friday nights, or at least it was the last time she’d checked. Without fail, he was home within five minutes. Dropping his keys down on the dining table he turned on the light and was surprised to see Rae seated there with her arms crossed in front of her chest. 
<br />
“Rae? What are you doing here?” he asked with a frown.
<br />
She stood up, drew her gun and approached him quickly. With the muzzle but a few inches from his face; she cocked the weapon but did not fire.
<br />
“What are you waiting for?” he demanded, putting his hands up in surrender, “Go ahead and kill me…” 
<br />
The look in his beautiful blue-green eyes was not one of horror or disgust but of sorrow and sadness. And the .9mm trembled in her hand – she could not find the strength to pull the trigger, “You’re letting me kill you?” Rae said calmly, masking her frustration at the fact that she was not able to shoot him. He wasn’t like the others she’d killed. They were strangers, but he… he was a partner, a friend in a life she couldn’t remember… 
<br />
Kai shrugged, “One of us has to die” he replied, “I’d rather it be me than you…” he said adamantly. 
<br />
Rae lowered her weapon, struck him hard across the cheek with the side of her gun, and then fled the apartment. Leaving Kai to stand alone in awe at what had just taken place. 
<br />
She’d failed. 
<br />
What would Esmé say? 
<br />
Would she have her killed? 
<br />
What was the consequence?
<br />

<br />
When Rae returned, Renata was already asleep, no, not asleep. In bed with Taylor which meant she had to the sleep on the couch, again. She had contemplated for a long time whether she ought to clean out her work room and move her bed and the rest of her belongings in there. Rena and Taylor’s late night entertainment was making her lose sleep. It wasn’t just that she couldn’t sleep in her room; it was the fact that they were so damn loud. She slipped a disk into her Playstation then flopped down on the couch with her wireless controller to pass the time – and even perhaps bore herself to sleep – she’d played Silent Hill 4 a million times before… 
<br />
Midnight came and not a minute after, the phone call came. Not on her cellphone – but her home phone. Rae didn’t bother to pick up and sat by the phone while it rang and rang until the answering machine picked up the call.
<br />

<br />
“The deadline has passed Rae and you have yet to deliver me what I want…This is the first time you’ve deliberately dodge a task until the point of failure. But upon reflection, I do realize just how hard it is to accomplish. You will have another week to bring me what I have asked.”
<br />

<br />
Rae buried her face in her hands in frustration. “What am I doing to do?” she looked up and stared at the framed picture of her and Kai as kids playing on the teeter totter sitting hanging on the wall facing her.
<br />
 She remembered nothing of that day, before it or after it leading up to a few months before her fifteenth birthday. There was nothing there – just blank space where memories should have been. She could still remember waking up in a hospital bed in great pain with tubes protruding from her nose and mouth without any knowledge of who she was or what she was doing there. 
<br />
She simply…was… 
<br />

<br />
“What would you do, Rae?” she muttered, “What would you do?”
<br />

<br />
Renata stormed out of her room a few minutes later, “What the fuck were you doing? You scared the shit out of us!” She exclaimed.
<br />
“Sorry…”Rae muttered, her eyes apparently glued to the television screen.
<br />
Renata shook her heads, “You and your video games…when will you ever learn to grow up girl? You’re not in grade four! ” she chuckled before returning to the room and slamming the door behind her. 
<br />
Great…lets listen to them have sex…again…Rae thought bitterly as she threw her controller aside then grabbed the keys and headed out into the lamp lit streets. She had no where to turn – Esmé was hounding her for a victim she couldn’t bring herself to kill – everywhere she went, Esmé would know; Renata was too busy with her boyfriend to care for anything…
<br />
Rae bought herself a cup of coffee at the café a block from her condominium and sat down with the burning paper cup in her hands, wondering how long it would last her before she was kicked out: as it turned out – two hours, until closing time. She left the coffee untouched along with a large tip before heading out again into the night…
<br />

<br />
Two days later, Rae was perched upon the roof of the building opposite the condominium where Kai lived. In the darkness of night, she was invisible. Pressing her cheek against the cold steel, she peered into the scope for the fourth time and adjusted her aim. He was sitting in his bedroom – working at his desk with a bottle of beer beside him. With her finger on the trigger, she prepared to fire. But found that she couldn’t kill him. 
<br />
She sighed. What can’t I just pull the trigger? He’s not staring me in the face! What was there to feel guilty about? What’s wrong with me? She though angrily as she took apart her rifle and put it away before heading back home. Though she had another five days to accomplish the task, she decided that she wasn’t about to try to kill him again. 
<br />

<br />
“Back so soon?” Renata sneered when she heard the door open.
<br />
Rae entered and slammed the door behind her without a word. She was obviously very, very angry. “Where’s the body?”
<br />
“There is no body now” she muttered, “But there will one be in five days – mine.”
<br />
Her friend sighed heavily, “You couldn’t kill him…” she muttered.
<br />
“No shit” Rae muttered under her breath as she flopped down on the couch and buried her hands in her face, “God! What the fuck is wrong with me?” she said, wringing her fingers until they turned white. “The first time I went in person and I thought I could do it for sure but there was that look in his eyes that I can’t describe…so sad –“
<br />
“So gently yet so lonely?” Renata interjected, “What is it now – you took the sniper rifle with you – what’s the problem this time round?”
<br />
Rae shook her head, “That’s what’s tearing me apart – I have no idea why” she growled, “I can’t do it. Doesn’t Esmé see that? Doesn’t she know that? She knows just about every other fucking little detail of our goddamned lives!” she exhaled deeply and composed her thoughts, “God, I sound like a fucking soap opera…”
<br />
Her roommate put a hand on her shoulder, “If you can’t kill him, then he was meant to live” she whispered.
<br />
“How?” she muttered, turning to her friend with a look of anguish on her face.
<br />
Renata smiled, “You’re superman – not me. You figure out how” she told her, “You always manage to pull through in the end, no matter what. And I believe you already know the answer…”
<br />

<br />
Kai opened the door with a look of surprise on his face, “Back again, are we?” he sneered. But Rae said nothing. Stepping inside, she pushed the door shut and reached into her coat pocket.
<br />
“Why didn’t you kill me last time?” Kai asked, “I know you’re after me now, did you expect to catch me off guard again?”
<br />
She pushed him into the dining room and shoved him into a chair, “I didn’t come here to kill you…” she said, “not this time…”
<br />
“Then what did you come to do?” he watched in silence as Rae opened a plastic case containing two small 5ml syringes filled with different coloured suspensions. “What is that?” he demanded, but Rae did not reply, taking the one of them she removed the cap but Kai drew back, “You’re going to get killed for this” he exclaimed, “You of all people should know that I’d rather die than live at the expense of other people’s lives!”
<br />
Rae scoffed, “Well, Kai…I’m not giving you a choice” she said adamantly as she grabbed his arm and jabbed the needle into one of the visible veins in his forearm. He winced in pain but said nothing more when the contents of the second needle were forced into his body. “That wasn’t so bad…was it?”
<br />
“Rae! Esmé is going to have you shot for this!”
<br />
She shrugged as she placed the syringes into the box and slipped the case back into her pocket, and with that she left – slamming the door behind her with a loud thud. 
<br />

<br />
                                                            *
<br />

<br />
Rae stepped out of the shower to the smell of toast, egg s and bacon – Renata was awake. “How was your run?” her roommate asked as she stepped into the kitchen.
<br />
She shrugged and poured herself a glass of water, “Same old…”
<br />
“I went to see Kai yesterday when you were at that race…”
<br />
Rae chuckled, “Are you two timing Taylor now? One guy not enough for you?”
<br />
Renata rolled her eyes and threw a towel at Rae.
<br />
“Okay…I was kidding!” she exclaimed, putting her hands up in mock surrender. 
<br />
“You’re not going to ask how he’s doing?”
<br />
Rae raised an eyebrow, “should I be?”
<br />
“Well, duh!” Renata muttered, “He is your partner after all…”
<br />
“Whatever” she said with a shrug, “We can’t all be kind and caring like you…”
<br />
Her roommate shook her head, “God! You’re hopeless…”
<br />
“Uh huh…”
<br />
                                                            *
<br />
 “Go! Go! Go!” Rae whispered.
<br />
“Are you fucking insane?” Kai snapped.
<br />
She shook her head, “I’ll cover for you…”
<br />
He rolled his eyes as he crept into the corridor full of guards having accomplished the mission – all that was left was to escape. Which turned out to be harder than anyone could ever imagine. “Fuck!” Rae muttered, hearing the sound of distant shots.
<br />
“Great…”
<br />
Rae sighed, “Go!”
<br />
“In there?”
<br />
“No! Out the exit you idiot!” she snapped as she pushed him out the storm of the machine gunfire and charged into it, “Leave the premises immediately!”
<br />
Kai sighed, “Fucking crazy bitch thinks she’s fucking invincible…” he muttered under his breath as he bolted for the exit. Half way there, he stopped, contemplating whether he should go back for her…but what did it matter? 
<br />
He went on and didn’t turn back.
<br />

<br />
Kai was troubled at the fact that Rae was not in school the following day when he looked around the biology classroom to find her seat empty. But he had no idea that this was to go on for several days.
<br />
“Rachel! Rachel Lindenmaier!” the teacher paused, “Absent again?”
<br />
Several classmates mutter amongst themselves.
<br />
“Can anyone get in touch with her and ask her what’s going on?”
<br />
“I told you yesterday and the day before, sir, she was into a motorcycle accident!” one of her friends muttered. That was a lie – Rae didn’t ride motorbikes- she hated them. But evidently, she couldn’t tell her friends she’d been shot or had the shit beaten out of her by a bunch of guards in the building she had broken in and stolen from.  
<br />
“Alright then…”
<br />
Kai sat with his cheek propped up against his knuckles in a thoughtful pose as he sat in the nearly empty classroom – wondering what had happened to Rae. He would have to go see her after school today – it’d been almost a week since the last mission and he had yet to hear from her. Something was definitely wrong.
<br />
He dialled her number as he approached the door of her apartment, suddenly remembering that she was bothered by people barging in. The phone rang and rang until finally, he heard the receiver being picked up.
<br />
“Hello? Rae?”
<br />
“Yeah. It’s me…” her voice sounded hoarse and groggy as if she had too many drinks, “To whom am I speaking?”
<br />
“It’s me Kai.”
<br />
She cleared her throat, “Can I help you?”
<br />
“Just checking if you were alright.”
<br />
“I’m fine, thank you.”
<br />
“Good. I’m standing outside your door as we speak. I’m coming in.”
<br />
“No…no. Everything’s fine”
<br />
He hung up abruptly and tried the door knob; the door was unlocked – how very unlike her. Stepping inside he shut the door quietly behind him. “Rae?” he muttered as he walked towards her bedroom.
<br />
“I said I was fine”, came a voice from within. She sounded even worse in person.
<br />
Kai paused at the doorway and peered into the room cautiously. The floor around her bed was littered with bloodstained bandages and old dressings. Rae lay in bed looking pale and wraithlike as if she hadn’t any food or sleep in years.
<br />
“You call this ‘fine’?” he snapped angrily as he bent over and began picking up the bloody dressings from the floor, “You’ll die like this.”
<br />
She shrugged, “Who cares. I’ve seen better days.” Even in her condition she was her old pessimistic self, Kai thought bitterly as he quickly exited her room to throw out the garbage and wash his hands. He ran to the kitchen and poured her a glass of water – as there was nothing else to drink, not a drop of milk or juice.
<br />
Kai rushed back into her room, “Why didn’t you call?” he demanded angrily as he set the glass on the night table and proceeded to help her sit up.
<br />
Rae took a sip and almost chocked, “Thanks” she muttered hoarsely but didn’t answer his question.
<br />
“I asked you a question…”
<br />
She shrugged, “It’s nothing serious.”
<br />
“Nothing serious?!” he growled, “Are you kidding me? Would you be lying in bed like this, half dead, if it was nothing serious?!”
<br />
“Alright, stop yelling!” she exclaimed.
<br />
Kai sighed, “I’m sorry. I was just worried about you…” he muttered.
<br />
“Thank you for your concern” she muttered monotonously as if it was obligatory.
<br />
He leaned forward and planted a kiss on her forehead, “Wait here. I’ll fix you something to eat, and then I’ll change your dressings.”
<br />
“I can –”
<br />
“Don’t argue. You’re the wounded one now.”
<br />

<br />
Kai returned a half hour later, “Dinner won’t be ready for another twenty minutes. Let’s get you cleaned up first. Uh…” he paused, wondering how he should go about getting her ‘cleaned up’. “Um…can you stand?”
<br />
“Yea…pretty much” she replied, “I can take care of myself. Don’t worry.”
<br />
He nodded, “Okay then. Why don’t you go take a shower?”
<br />
She nodded and sat up slowly, then got out of the bed in the same fashion – still quite shaky on her feet. He turned back to the mess on her bed – the sheets and covers were smeared with blood – dark and rusty. They would need to be changed. Kai found a new set in the linen closest then stripped down the old covers and tossed them aside. Who knew that someone could bleed so much? And how could Esmé possibly leave her in such a state?
<br />
Rae turned on the hot water and let it run over her body – the water swirling around her feet was pink with her own blood as she scrubbed vigorously at the dried blood crusted on her skin. Every part of her body hurt, every limb, every muscle, even her scalp hurt from falling into the bed of broken glass upon her grand exit – a suicidal jump out a fifth floor. But she was still quite lucky; having suffered only two shots – one to the left shoulder and the other to her arm. When she finally got out of the shower, Kai was already gone – he’d left a note on her night table. 
<br />
It’s almost 6 – Esmé will be home soon. I think its best if I leave before then. Pasta and sauce is on the stove, there are lamb chops in the oven – enjoy yourself and I hope you like it! <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="Smile" border="0" /> See you later! (but with Esmé around 24/7I don’t think I will be able to for the next little while…). Take care of yourself!
<br />
                                                     Love, Kai.
<br />
Rae crumpled the note in her hand, threw it into the toilet and flushed it. Stuff like this shouldn’t be left lying around otherwise, dire consequences will follow. And Rae was sure that neither she nor Kai were ready to face them, whatever they may be. Just then  
<br />

<br />
Rae sipped her drink to fill up the empty silence and searched her brain for something to talk about but –
<br />
“Hey cutie!” a high pitched voice giggled from behind them.
<br />
She turned around to see a woman who approached Kai and proceeded to sit down beside him, acting in a rather provocative manner. “What’s your name?” she asked. Kai turned the other way and ignored her, eyes fixed upon Rae. After a few attempts to make conversation, the woman left apparently very angry.
<br />
“Kai, you’re such a prude” Rae exclaimed when she was sure that the lady was out of earshot, “She was only flirting.”
<br />
He laughed, “Look who’s talking…”
<br />
“I’m not a prude!” she protested.
<br />
“Yes you are!”
<br />
“No I’m not!”
<br />
“Then kiss me!” Kai told her.
<br />
Rae laughed, “No.”
<br />
“Well, I proved my point…” he said with a smirk.
<br />
“Fine. I’ll prove it!” 
<br />
She leaned in, closing the space between them, several centimetres from his face, Rae burst out laughing, “I can’t do it.”
<br />
“Prude…” he muttered then sipped his drink; eyes still fixed intently upon her as he did so. She held his gaze for a few moments before a spot of colour appeared on her cheeks and she turned away, clearly embarrassed. Kai set down his shot glass and reached across the counter to put his hand over hers the squeezed it gently. Rae looked up, smiled but said nothing more. He inched his face closer and closer to her until their lips brushed and he kissed her. This time, she did not protest. To his surprise, she opened her mouth and kissed him back, slow and gentle.
<br />
Rae turned her gaze toward the display of glasses across from her when the kiss ended, red and embarrassed once again. She inhaled deeply and let out at soft chuckle, “Yeah, you’re right. I am a prude.” She muttered, “I’m all red and it was only a kiss…”
<br />
“It doesn’t have to be “only a kiss”…” he told her.
<br />
She stared at him blankly for a while then turned back to her drink, not knowing what she ought to say. 
<br />

<br />

<br />
“Let’s review the density of an Ideal Gas at STP…”
<br />
Rae sighed softly for the sixth time in the past five minutes– trying her hardest to stay awake. Density equalled molar mass over molar volume – the same as it was yesterday. Neither chemistry nor anything, as a matter of fact, was of any interest to her at the moment. Her eyelids felt heavy from the heavy dose of morphine she’d given herself before school to suppress the pain of her wounds. And now that it was slowly wearing off – the dull, throbbing sensation was slowly returning to her body – it was the only thing keeping her awake. Suddenly her phone vibrated in her pocket, making her jump. As soon as the teacher turned back the board – she slipped it out of its hiding place.
<br />
NEW TEXT MESSAGE
<br />

<br />
r u ok?
<br />
how r u holdin’ up? 
<br />
still alive?
<br />
meet me after class
<br />
 &lt;3 Kai
<br />

<br />
  Rae smiled to herself as she quickly typed her reply:
<br />
yea…kinda sleepy thou
<br />
i’ll b alright, no worries <img src="images/smiles/icon_biggrin.gif" alt="Very Happy" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
He was waiting outside her chemistry class when she finally dragged herself out of her desk. Taking the books from her, he escorted her outside, “You should have stayed home…” he told her, “You look like one of those crackheads smoking their heads off outside like there’s no tomorrow….”
<br />
Rae laughed, “Just 10 cc’s of morphine – its not so bad” she protested, “anyways, it’s wearing off and I’m already less sleepy…let’s go to bio”. Kai shook his head, “You can’t go to class like this…” he told her, “come on – let’s get out of here.” 
<br />
“Playing hooky again?”
<br />
He shrugged, “who cares…I only came to school to see you anyways…”<br />_________________<br /><img src="http://i48.photobucket.com/albums/f205/ds_mikage/Shinimegamicopy.jpg" border="0" /></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
